Activity Name: Recovery one testing out Hoka shoes
Activity Description:
Recent synthesis research suggests that alternating shoes is important for recovery and reduced likelihood of injury. I have always been a one-shoe runner. Wide toebox (2-4E) with cushioning has been my goal. Generally, I ran in Kayano shoes. Then at a certain mileage, swap in new shoes, next model up same line. However, in 2017, I am working to improve my biomechanics and took the opportunity to switch to zero-drop, wide toebox, minimal cushioned shoes.

My goal is run with wide shoe to encourage toe splay, 20-25mm stack height, zero drop. However, I am exploring the value of an alt-shoe for recovery. Enter Hoka.

Hoka Arahi comes in 2E. Reasonably wide toebox. Stretchy 3D printed upper so stretches on run. A 5mm drop, 29mm stack. So more cushioned than I prefer and also a wedge. Could be good for longer runs and recovery.

Review
The 2E option is wide but could be a bit wider.
Responsive within 5-7mins of running.
Not a firm ride but good pronation control.
Upper does stretch out.
Cushioning allows for more error in biomechanics. This is both bad and good. Bad, you can drift back towards heels. Good, if you can maintain habit/attention, the cushioning in mid and forefoot is very nice to recover.
Once you adapt to landing, it is unlikely these shoes will slow you down even if you are accustomed to more minimal cushioning or a relatively more rigid ride.

Bottom line (or foot): significant cushioning, surprisingly responsive, pronation control sufficient, could be a bit wider.

Activity Name: Recovery swim (if that is a real thing)
Money for nothing, runs for free
Activity Description:
Decision time. Train in minimalist shoes (zero drop, limited stack height, & very firm ride) or in cushioned shoes (5mm drop & significant cushioning)?

Running free (not free-running) for me is pure delight.  No music, check watch rarely, drift towards a 10-min mile pace, and enjoy being outside. Minimalist shoes literally ensure I remain in touch with my footfalls and form and encourage me to stay mindful and connected to every step. More cushioned shoes do not.  

I am going to try for minimalist until my body signals otherwise. Improvements in for m likely offset increased risk of injury. I will 'save' the cushioned, wedge shoes for end of weekly cycle runs for now and see how that works. I think different shoes at the end of a run cycle also provide a 'fresh' feel to the training, physical and psychological placebo, that can bump up those final runs before a rest day.

Consult with Dr Brisby (Chiro and Sport Physio) yesterday on next phase of rehab. New strategy or next phase to Achilles tear repair. 

Phase 1.  A total of three weeks. Little to no running. Keep blood flowing and stay flexible. 

Phase 2.  Run as often, as hard, or as far as you like. However, the moment it starts to hurt (or you climb even up one point on the discomfort scale) you stop immediately, walk and end workout. 

#fieldnote: on discomfort scale, a score of 1, that began at mile 2, then faded for next mile, then Achilles just felt hot for remainder of run. So, I pushed it out another mile for a total of 5 miles. Baby steps I know, but I want to do active recovery and not undue damage and not be able to run.

#fieldnotes: Achilles was sore in morning on the walk to work. Day off from running to be safe. Swim makes all the pain and tightness disappear from tendon.

The day on, day off presents some trade-offs. Advantage primarily is that it allows tendon to recovery (limited blood flow to recommended to give it time between runs). This seems to be working. Disadvantages for me at least are that it is challenging to build momentum.  In a multi-day run cycle, the trail runs improve.  The first run is ok but always feels sluggish. Subsequent runs feel really great with more endorphins and oxytocin too. So, this current regime is allowing what I hope is permanent and solid tendon repair but every run is a 'first' run and a little less gratifying.  Patience.

Further to the awesome suggestions from Leah Wasser and Elizabeth Forbes, I tested a theory with a run today. #theory: achilles tendon damage fully/mostly recovered (i.e. tears are healed up), and current discomfort experiencing due to tightness in calves and other surrounding supportive systems. Today was third consecutive run this week. #predictions: if tear and direct within tendon issues, it will be sore; if supporting tissue it will be not. To test, did the run, but last night was tight so literally did 15minutes of deep tissue massage in area including calves (without roller), stretching, and some essential oils to loosen up region particularly in right left where tendon was torn this summer. #outcome: A totally pain free fun.  I 'know' that my running improves over consecutive days because I generally get less stiff and this plus a tiny bit of deep massage totally did the trick!  So, I am going to move my thinking and approach now to incorporate the suggestions from runners from recovery to prevention. Whew!

Exploring two within run #runhacks to reduce tendon sensitivity. 
1. Ensure upper body well balanced over center of mass to reduce strain on Achilles. Be upright not forward or slouchy. 
2. Keep cadence up to >80 to reduce per footfall strain. This also encourages engaging psoas muscles and glutes more to keep up reasonable turnover.

Activity Description: Mindful that a disaster is just a few miles away.

Lazy runner because I just want to put on shoes, get outside, and run. Stretching, foam rollers, massage, and other interventions are all amazing of course. However, time is also a factor, and I love being outside. So, if I can spend my time outside, running, and ensure achilles tendon recovery continues, that is a big win!

Hypothesis:
Attention to biomechanics can facilitate better tendon recovery. 

Gear: 
Ears, a watch that estimates cadence, and/or Lumo Run for more detailed form data.

Tips:
1. Run lightly.  Runners that were asked to run quietly had better form and less impact. 

2. Keep cadence high. I am tying for 85rpm or 170spm. Higher turnover keeps your feet under you, reduces impact, and prevents over-reaching on each stride. 

3. Kick back a bit. With higher cadence and less reaching forward, add a little heel kick back up on strokes. For me, this shifts my foot strike forward a bit off heel, massively reduces brakes, and takes strain off my achilles.

Super challenging to maintain a high turnover. Be a neat idea to run as best you can in terms of form and stop when you cannot. 

Lumo Run data confirms how challenging this run felt. So hard to run with rapid little steps. So hard. 

On the upside, zero pain in tendon.  It is not easy to get a kick in with little steps though so need to figure out if it is cadence or kick back that will protect tendon.

Activity Name: A total of 4 things you can do on a run
Activity Description:
In descending order of preference.

1. #runthoughts: pay attention for form, listen to breathing, look around, enjoy the scenery, challenge yourself.

2. #problemsolve: ideate, solve a problem, work on a solution to a challenge.

3. #randomthoughts: happy or otherwise, just let stuff float around

4. #fret: my least favorite, #longloop reflect on a negative issue and/or worry. 'possible' that in some respects it is good to give yourself space to work through and not bury stuff you are worried about, but not that much fun.

Rationale: accidental find of this book:
https://www.amazon.com/Mindful-Running-Meditative-Performance-Fulfilled/dp/1472944860

I will give it a read and let you know what I think.

Activity Name: Non-orthotic test run: experimental design at its finest
Activity Description:
Next run, only one insert. Ha, kidding.

#fieldnotes
Permeable
Huge difference in cushioning going back to non-orthotic running
Much more impact into big toe and push off

Impermeable
Ok without orthotics, feels great on dirt and grass

Biomechanics
Without orthotics, better mechanics, turnover, lighter running, and can feel the ground better.
Downside is an an impact cost, only on permeable surfaces to get to trail, that hurts big toe a big.

Activity Name: I think I understand orthotics now run: it is all about energy return
Activity Description:
A colleague and best friend did gait scan and 3D foot analyses. The orthotics provide support under ball of foot to mitigate pressure on big toe push off.  Cushioning and heel post.

Superfeet blue insoles weigh 90g.
The custom orthotics come in at 190g so an extra 50g you need turn over per kick.

Use
1. Fantastic for recovery in wide, neutral preferably zero-drop shoes (ie comfy Altras).
2. A bit of challenge to turn over in running and in energy return. Best guess is combination of weight and type of foam does not return sufficient energy (which interacts with potential reduces in cadence). 

Bottom line (or foot)
These inserts for these feet and this runner (mid-to-forefoot striker) super for recovery but a challenge to run. Built for cushioning not responsiveness.
